%{snippet|id=tutorial|file=${basedir}/src/main/java/net/officefloor/tutorial/springrestcors/SpringRestCorsApplication.java|ignoreDownloadError=false}



*Approach 1 — CORS configured in the YAML composition

  CORS rules can be placed directly in the endpoint YAML file under a top-level <<<composition: cors:>>>
  key.  All fields of {{{/apidocs/net/officefloor/spring/starter/rest/cors/ComposeCorsConfiguration.html}ComposeCorsConfiguration}}
  are available: <<<allowed-origins>>>, <<<allowed-origin-patterns>>>, <<<allowed-methods>>>,
  <<<allowed-headers>>>, <<<exposed-headers>>>, <<<allow-credentials>>>, <<<allow-private-network>>>,
  and <<<max-age>>>.

%{snippet|file=${basedir}/src/main/resources/officefloor/rest/cors/composition.GET.yml|ignoreDownloadError=false}

  The service class itself has no CORS knowledge — it just responds:

%{snippet|id=tutorial|file=${basedir}/src/main/java/net/officefloor/tutorial/springrestcors/CompositionCorsService.java|ignoreDownloadError=false}



*Approach 2 — <<<@CrossOrigin>>> annotation on the service class

  Spring's standard <<<@CrossOrigin>>> annotation placed on the service class is discovered by
  OfficeFloor at startup.  It walks the composition graph of each endpoint and collects every
  <<<@CrossOrigin>>> it finds, merging the results.

%{snippet|id=tutorial|file=${basedir}/src/main/java/net/officefloor/tutorial/springrestcors/AnnotationCorsService.java|ignoreDownloadError=false}

  The YAML file needs no CORS configuration — the annotation is enough:

%{snippet|file=${basedir}/src/main/resources/officefloor/rest/cors/annotation.GET.yml|ignoreDownloadError=false}



*Testing

  Tests send an <<<Origin>>> header.  When the origin is on the allow-list the response carries
  <<<Access-Control-Allow-Origin>>>.  When it is not, Spring returns <<<403 Forbidden>>> and the
  header is absent:

%{snippet|id=tutorial|file=${basedir}/src/test/java/net/officefloor/tutorial/springrestcors/SpringRestCorsTest.java|ignoreDownloadError=false}



